User groups

This system will be used by several different groups, all interacting with The Mat Works in different ways. Understanding who these users are helps shape the features the system needs to include.
Public Customers
These are people visiting the venue for events, gigs, exhibitions, or to use the café/bar. Their main interaction with the system is browsing events, buying tickets, and accessing basic information about the venue.
Musicians and Bands
These users rely on the venue for rehearsal spaces and equipment. They need a simple way to check availability, make bookings, and manage their hire sessions without needing to contact staff directly.
Operational Staff
This includes frontofhouse staff, technicians, booking coordinators, and café/bar employees. They need access to scheduling, bookings, and daytoday operational details to keep things running smoothly.
Management
Managers require higherlevel access, such as reports on bookings, revenue, equipment usage, staffing levels, and overall performance. Their priority is understanding the business data behind the venue.
 
 
 
Current Situation / Operational Challenges

Although The Mat Works provides a wide range of services, much of their current booking and management process is handled manually. This leads to several challenges that affect both customers and staff:
Booking Confusion
Using paper forms, phone calls, or separate spreadsheets increases the risk of mistakes. Doublebooking rooms or equipment is a real possibility.
High Staff Workload
Staff spend time handling enquiries, chasing information, and updating records. This reduces time they could spend on supporting customers or improving the venue experience.
Limited Tracking and Reporting
Because the data isn't centralised, it’s difficult for management to get accurate insight into revenue, usage levels, or which services are performing well.
Customer Experience Issues
Public users and musicians don’t have a clear online system for booking or checking availability. This makes the process slower and less convenient.
Overall Inefficiency
The current system doesn’t scale well as demand increases, meaning the venue risks losing bookings or missing opportunities to improve operations.
 
 
 
Business Goals

The aim of the new system is to support the venue’s growth, improve the customer experience, and make internal processes much more efficient. The key goals include:
Efficient Booking Management
A centralised system that lets staff and customers manage bookings easily and reduces the risk of errors.
Improved Customer Experience
Clear navigation, easy ticket purchasing, and quick access to information about facilities and availability.
Better Inventory and Resource Tracking
Ensuring equipment, rooms, and staff schedules are accurately managed and always up to date.
Secure User Accounts
Allowing customers, musicians, and staff to safely access the services they need with proper authentication.
Data Reporting and Insights
Giving the management team accurate data on revenue, usage statistics, and performance trends to support decisionmaking.
 
 
 
Problem Breakdown

The Mat Works operates several services at the same time, which creates a number of operational challenges that a digital management system needs to solve. These challenges can be broken down into the following key problem areas.
Problem Area | Description of Issue | Impact on the Business
Ticket Sales Management | Ticket sales, seat allocation and event information are currently handled manually or across different tools, which can lead to errors or outdated information. | Risk of double bookings, frustrated customers, and potential loss of revenue during busy events.
Rehearsal Room Scheduling | Musicians often book rehearsal rooms at overlapping times, and staff currently track this manually. | Time clashes, unhappy customers, and confusion for staff organising room availability.
Equipment Inventory Control | Equipment such as microphones, amps and lighting is used by multiple bands. Without a realtime system, availability isn’t always accurate. | Overbooking equipment, lastminute cancellations, and damage to the venue’s reputation.
User Account Handling | Different users (public, musicians, staff, management) all need different permissions. Without proper access levels, information can be exposed or misused. | Security risks, GDPR concerns, and loss of trust from users.
Operational Admin Workload | Staff spend a lot of time manually updating records, confirming bookings, and handling enquiries. | Staff burnout, time wasted, and slower service for customers.
Lack of Business Reporting | The venue currently has limited ways to analyse booking data or track revenue trends across services. | Management have weaker decisionmaking power and may miss opportunities to increase efficiency or income.
 
 
 
