Test Strategy
 
A structured test strategy ensures that every part of the system functions correctly, meets the client requirements, and provides a reliable experience for all user groups. Testing will be carried out throughout development to identify issues early, maintain quality, and confirm that the final system is stable, secure, and userfriendly. The table below outlines the key testing types that will be used for The Mat Works system.
 
Test Type

Purpose

Example Test

Functional Testing

Ensures each feature works as intended and meets the requirements.

Confirm that musicians can successfully book a rehearsal room (R7).

Validation Testing

Checks that user inputs are correct, safe, and handled properly.

Ensure email fields reject invalid formats during registration (R4).

Security Testing

Confirms that authentication, permissions, and data protection are secure.

Verify that staff cannot access managementonly features (R16–R19).

Usability Testing

Ensures the interface is easy to navigate and understand.

Test that public users can find and purchase tickets without confusion (R2–R3).

Performance Testing

Checks system behaviour under load or high activity.

Simulate multiple users booking rooms at the same time.

Compatibility Testing

Ensures the system works across different devices and browsers.

Test the site on mobile, tablet, and desktop.

Integration Testing

Confirms that different components work together correctly.

Ensure that booking a rehearsal room also updates equipment availability.

User Acceptance Testing (UAT)

Final approval from real users to confirm the system meets expectations.

Staff test the admin dashboard to confirm it supports daily operations.

This testing strategy ensures that the final system is robust, secure, and fully aligned with the needs of The Mat Works and its users.
 
 
 
